a><article class="blog-markdown mx-auto max-w-screen-md prose prose-hr:h-[8px] prose-hr:m-0 prose-hr:border-none prose-headings:my-0 prose-headings:font-700 prose-headings:text-charcoal prose-h1:mb-[32px] prose-h1:mt-[48px] prose-h1:text-[34px] prose-h1:leading-[40px] prose-h1:tracking-[0.25px] md:prose-h1:text-[48px] md:prose-h1:leading-[56px] md:prose-h1:tracking-[0px] lg:prose-h1:text-[60px] lg:prose-h1:leading-[72px] prose-h2:text-[24px] prose-h2:leading-[32px] prose-h2:tracking-[0px] prose-h2:mt-[48px] prose-h2:mb-[24px] md:prose-h2:text-[34px] md:prose-h2:leading-[40px] md:prose-h2:tracking-[0.25px] lg:prose-h2:text-[40px] lg:prose-h2:leading-[48px] lg:prose-h2:tracking-[0px] prose-h3:text-[20px] prose-h3:leading-[32px] prose-h3:tracking-[0.15px] prose-h3:mb-[20px] md:prose-h3:text-[24px] md:prose-h3:leading-[32px] md:prose-h3:tracking-[0px] prose-p:m-0 prose-p:font-500 prose-p:text-charcoal prose-p:text-[14px] prose-p:leading-[24px] prose-p:tracking-[0.1px] prose-p:mb-[20px] md:prose-p:text-[16px] md:prose-p:leading-[32px] md:prose-p:tracking-[0.15px] prose-a:text-blue prose-strong:font-700 prose-blockquote:border-none prose-blockquote:relative prose-p:before:content-[] prose-blockquote:not-italic prose-blockquote:m-0 prose-blockquote:p-[8px_0px_8px_16px] md:prose-blockquote:p-[8px_0px_8px_26px] prose-blockquote:before:absolute prose-blockquote:before:inset-0 prose-blockquote:before:w-[4px] prose-blockquote:before:bg-blue prose-blockquote:before:rounded-full prose-blockquote:before:left-0 md:prose-blockquote:before:w-[6px] prose-ol:pl-[16px] prose-ol:mb-[20px] prose-ol:list-decimal md:prose-ol:pl-[26px] prose-li:marker:proportional-nums prose-ul:pl-[16px] prose-ul:mb-[20px] prose-ul:list-disc md:prose-ul:pl-[26px] prose-li:font-500 prose-li:text-charcoal prose-li:text-[16px] prose-li:leading-[32px] prose-li:m-0 prose-li:p-0 prose-table:table-fixed prose-table:border-[0px] prose-table:text-charcoal prose-table:text-[14px] prose-table:leading-[24px] md:prose-table:text-[16px] prose-tr:grid prose-tr:divide-y-[3px] prose-tr:divide-lavender prose-tr:border-[0px] sm:prose-tr:border-[3px] sm:prose-tr:border-lavender sm:prose-tr:table-row prose-td:p-[32px] sm:prose-td:border-[3px] sm:prose-td:border-lavender prose-th:p-[32px] empty:prose-th:hidden sm:empty:prose-th:table-cell sm:prose-th:border-[3px] sm:prose-th:border-lavender prose-thead:border-[3px] prose-thead:border-lavender prose-tbody:border-[3px] prose-tbody:border-lavender prose-tbody:divide-y-[3px] prose-tbody:divide-lavender"><p>This is the step where you do reference checks to see if everything the candidate has shared is, in fact, true. A good idea is to call or email the potential candidate&#x2019;s reference and ask the following question: &#x201C;Would you hire this candidate again?&#x201D;</p>
<h3>7. Wrapping Up</h3>
<p>Last but certainly not least is the end of the interview. This is a very subtle but important thing to do to leave potential candidates feeling good about your company culture.</p>
<p>Thank the potential employee for their time and walk them to the exit as getting lost in a new environment is easy.</p>
<p>Also, this will prevent the potential candidates from feeling embarrassed.</p>
<p>Additionally, it is crucial to send a follow-up email to every potential candidate, whether it be a job offer or a <a href="https://flair.hr/en/blog/job-rejection-letter/" rel="noopener">job rejection email</a>. By doing this, you&#x2019;re avoiding the chance of job candidates posting negative reviews about your company&#x2019;s interview process.</p>
<h2 id="tipstechniquestobeagoodinterviewer">Tips &amp; Techniques To Be A Good Interviewer</h2>
<p>A huge part of having a successful interview is to be aware of the right techniques at your disposal to use during the interview.</p>
<h3>Qualities Of A Good Interviewer</h3>
<p>Let&#x2019;s start by defining some of the qualities of a good interviewer. These are some things that are non-negotiable and will play a vital role in conducting a good interview with a potential client. Even though some of them may seem obvious, it is important to take these qualities to heart to ensure the success of your interview.</p>
<ul>
<li>Be friendly to get the most out of your potential candidates to select the right candidate for the job.</li>
<li>Don&#x2019;t be biased; this includes looking for shared characteristics with the potential candidate or relying on first impressions.</li>
<li>Don&#x2019;t waste time with unnecessary questions: this also revolves around the idea of structuring your interview beforehand and planning the right questions to ask.</li>
<li>Be professional at all times as the interview process leaves an overall impression about the company.</li>
<li>Be honest: Along with this point, we have to mention that it is crucial to expect honesty while being honest. In other words, there will be tough questions coming your way about the company most likely, and it is best to always remain honest and positive. For example, just as a candidate can spin their weaknesses to be strengths, interviewers can mention negative aspects of their work in a positive light.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Must-Have Interview Techniques</h3>
<p>The following techniques aren&#x2019;t necessarily ones you should write down and make part of your structured interview. But instead, these are techniques to keep in mind throughout the process. Hopefully, these techniques will help you to guide the process.</p>
<h4>1. The STAR Method</h4>
<p>The STAR method is a technique that can be used by both interviewers and interviewees.</p>
<p>This method is used to answer questions thoroughly or, if you&#x2019;re an interviewer, to listen carefully and to notice if there is information missing in the answers that your candidates are providing. By doing this, you can better guide the interviewee and the process in general. This method is an excellent way to respond to behavioral-based interview questions. The action step is especially important when you&#x2019;re an interviewer.</p>
<p>STAR is an acronym for the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Situation - A relevant situation the candidate found themselves to be in.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Task - A specific goal the candidate worked towards while working on the task at hand.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Action - Action relates to the specific action the potential candidate took to reach the goal. This is where the STAR method becomes truly useful other than guiding the process. If the potential candidate doesn&#x2019;t provide enough information about any of the steps, you can simply ask them to elaborate.</p>
<p>However, if the candidate cannot elaborate on the action they took to achieve the goal at hand, it is likely that the candidate didn&#x2019;t actually participate in that task. This is because when someone has struggled with a task, they can usually tell you exactly how they resolved the situation.</p>
<p>On the contrary, if someone says they participated in a task but cannot give enough information as to how they attained their objectives, it is most likely that the candidate may not be telling the truth.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Result - Candidates should describe the positive result of actions they have taken to reach a goal.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>2. Review CVs</h3>
